 "NASA Goddard Space Flight Center", "location": "Greenbelt, MD, United States"}}, "id": "3809d72f5c9c4f9990fc8f26a5ea4a5a"}, {"sequence": 15, "submissionId": 20130014785, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Macintosh, Bruce"}, "organization": {"name": "Lawrence Livermore National Lab.", "location": "Livermore, CA, United States"}}, "id": "82e4187b3ca1432d845fdbdd8abd1c99"}, {"sequence": 16, "submissionId": 20130014785, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Malhotra, Sangeeta"}, "organization": {"name": "Arizona State Univ.", "location": "Tempe, AZ, United States"}}, "id": "8cb9f24615044f8492e8d79c93701c27"}, {"sequence": 17, "submissionId": 20130014785, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Penny, Matthew"}, "organization": {"name": "Ohio State Univ.", "location": "Columbus, OH, United States"}}, "id": "a37cf3ba22bc4b60bc1d566e6d74e3a7"}, {"sequence": 18, "submissionId": 20130014785, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Shaklan, Stuart"}, "organization": {"name": "Jet Propulsion Lab., California Inst. of Tech.", "location": "Pasadena, CA, United States"}}, "id": "4afafb2129c640c69dcca1dd5f0f8abb"}, {"sequence": 19, "submissionId": 20130014785, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Stern, Daniel"}, "organization": {"name": "Jet Propulsion Lab., California Inst. of Tech.", "location": "Pasadena, CA, United States"}}, "id": "51d16d9828dc4f218cb6d515beb7bcd6"}], "stiTypeDetails": "Preprint (Draft being sent to journal)", "technicalReviewType": "TECHNICAL_REVIEW_TYPE_NONE", "id": 20130014785, "created": "2013-12-19T08:43:50.0970000+00:00", "center": {"code": "GSFC", "name": "Goddard Space Flight Center", "id": "973fae00c3584b9fb4c762ae9870d0f6"}, "onlyAbstract": false, "sensitiveInformation": 2, "abstract": "We discuss scientific, technical, and programmatic issues related to the use of an NRO 2.4m telescope for the WFIRST initiative of the 2010 Decadal Survey. We show that this implementation of WFIRST, which we call \"NEW WFIRST,\" would achieve the goals of the NWNH Decadal Survey for the WFIRST core programs of Dark Energy and Microlensing Planet Finding, with the crucial benefit of deeper and/or wider near-IR surveys for GO science and a potentially Hubble-like Guest Observer program. NEW WFIRST could also include a coronagraphic imager for direct detection of dust disks and planets around neighboring stars, a high-priority science and technology precursor for future ambitious programs to image Earth-like planets around neighboring stars.", "isLessonsLearned": false, "disseminated": "DOCUMENT_AND_METADATA", "publications": [{"submissionId": 20130014785, "id": "c005fa58636e44229d7401f0f5041e1c", "publicationDate": "2013-01-01T00:00:00.0000000+00:00"}], "status": "CURATED", "related": [], "downloads": [{"draft": false, "mimetype": "application/pdf", "name": "20130014785.pdf", "type": "STI", "links": {"original": "/api/citations/20130014785/downloads/20130014785.pdf", "pdf": "/api/citations/20130014785/downloads/20130014785.pdf", "fulltext": "/api/citations/20130014785/downloads/20130014785.txt"}}], "downloadsAvailable": true, "index": "submissions-2022-09-30-06-07"}